        <h2>Discussion: Singleton Pattern for State Management</h2>
        <p>In this example, we used the singleton pattern to manage the theme state. Here's a breakdown of its pros, cons, and when alternatives like dependency injection might be more appropriate:</p>

        <h3>Pros of the Singleton Pattern:</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Global Access and Consistency:</strong> The singleton ensures that only one instance of the theme manager exists, providing a single point of truth for the theme state. This makes it easy to access and update the theme from anywhere in the application, as seen in the toggle button handler.</li>
            <li><strong>Resource Efficiency:</strong> It prevents multiple instances from being created, which is useful for managing shared resources like configuration or state (e.g., user preferences). In this case, it efficiently handles theme switching without redundancy.</li>
            <li><strong>Simplicity in Small Applications:</strong> For a self-contained file like this, it's straightforward to implement and understand, reducing boilerplate code.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Cons of the Singleton Pattern:</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Tight Coupling:</strong> The singleton creates global dependencies, making the code harder to test and maintain. For instance, if we wanted to mock the theme manager for unit testing, it's challenging because it's a global object.</li>
            <li><strong>Global State Issues:</strong> It can lead to unintended side effects if not managed carefully, as any part of the code can access and modify the state. In larger applications, this might cause bugs that are hard to trace.</li>
