        <p>Dependency injection (DI) is a better choice in more complex scenarios. DI involves passing dependencies (like the theme manager) explicitly to components that need them, rather than relying on a global instance. Here's when DI might be preferred:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Larger Applications:</strong> In apps with multiple modules or components, DI promotes modularity and reusability. For example, you could inject a theme manager into specific components, making it easier to swap implementations (e.g., for A/B testing themes).</li>
            <li><strong>Improved Testability:</strong> DI allows you to mock dependencies during testing, isolating components. With singletons, you'd have to deal with global state, which complicates tests.</li>
            <li><strong>Avoiding Global State:</strong> If your app needs to handle multiple contexts (e.g., different users with their own themes), DI enables creating separate instances without global pollution. In frameworks like Angular or React, DI is built-in and helps manage state more cleanly.</li>
            <li><strong>Best Practices in Modern Development:</strong> For projects using ES modules or frameworks, DI aligns better with principles like inversion of control, leading to cleaner, more maintainable code. If this example were expanded into a full web app, I'd recommend using a state management library like Redux (with DI principles) instead of a raw singleton.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>In summary, while the singleton works well for this simple, self-contained demo, consider DI for anything more substantial to enhance flexibility and avoid potential pitfalls.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- JavaScript for Theme Management using Singleton Pattern -->
    <script>
        // Singleton Pattern Implementation
        const ThemeManager = (function() {
            // Private variables and functions
            let instance; // Store the single instance
            let currentTheme = 'light'; // Default theme

            function createInstance() {
                return {
                    getTheme: function() {
                        return currentTheme;
                    },

                    setTheme: function(newTheme) {
                        if (newTheme === 'light' || newTheme === 'dark') {
                            currentTheme = newTheme;
                            applyTheme(); // Apply the theme to the DOM
                        } else {
                            console.error('Invalid theme. Use "light" or "dark".');
                        }
                    },

                    toggleTheme: function() {
                        currentTheme = (currentTheme === 'light' ? 'dark' : 'light');
                        applyTheme(); // Apply the new theme
                    }
                };

                // Private helper function to apply the theme
                function applyTheme() {
                    document.body.className = currentTheme + '-theme'; // Add or update the class on body
                }
            }

            return {
                getInstance: function() {
                    if (!instance) {
                        instance = createInstance();
                    }
                    return instance;
                }
            };
