    <h2>Discussion on the Singleton Pattern</h2>
    <p>The Singleton pattern is used here to manage the theme state. It ensures that only one instance of the theme manager exists, providing a global point of access to toggle and retrieve the current theme. Below, we discuss its pros, cons, and alternatives.</p>

    <h3>Pros of the Singleton Pattern:</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Global Access and Control:</strong> It provides a single point of access to the theme state, making it easy to manage and update across the entire application without passing instances around.</li>
        <li><strong>Resource Efficiency:</strong> In scenarios like this, where you need to control a shared resource (e.g., the theme state), Singleton prevents multiple instances from being created, which can save memory and ensure consistency.</li>
        <li><strong>Simplicity for Small Applications:</strong> For simple use cases, like this demo, it's straightforward to implement and use, as it centralizes logic in one place.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Cons of the Singleton Pattern:</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Global State Issues:</strong> Singletons introduce global state, which can lead to tight coupling between parts of the code. This makes the application harder to test, debug, and maintain, as changes in one place can unexpectedly affect others.</li>
        <li><strong>Difficulty in Testing:</strong> Unit testing becomes challenging because the Singleton's instance is shared, making it hard to mock or isolate dependencies. For example, in this demo, you'd have to reset the theme state manually for each test.</li>
