    </ul>

    <h3>When is Dependency Injection a Better Choice?</h3>
    <p>Dependency Injection (DI) is often preferable when you want to make your code more modular, testable, and flexible. Instead of relying on a global Singleton, DI involves passing dependencies (like the theme manager) explicitly to the components that need them. This avoids global state and makes it easier to swap implementations.</p>
    <p>For instance, in a larger application, you could inject the theme manager into specific components via constructors or functions. This would:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Improve testability by allowing you to mock the theme manager in unit tests.</li>
